To integrate $\int_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \cos(\theta) \ \text{d}\theta$, we recognize that the integrand is a cosine function, which integrates to the sine function.

&#x20;  &#x20;

$$
\begin{array}{rl}\int\limits_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \cos(\theta) \, \text{d}\theta & = \int\limits_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \cos(\theta) \, \text{d}\theta \\

\\

& = \left[ \sin(\theta) \right]_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}}

\end{array}


$$

&#x20;    &#x20;

***

&#x20;  &#x20;

Substitute the bounds:

&#x20; &#x20;

$$
\begin{array}{rl}\int\limits_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \cos(\theta) \, \text{d}\theta & = \left[ \sin(\theta) \right]_0^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \\

\\

& = \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\right) - \sin(0) \\

\\

& = 1 - 0 \\

\\

& = 1

\end{array}
$$

